}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=h&pubNum=176284&cite=0233275901&originatingDoc=I9d401a5c0bf411d9bc18e8274af85244&refType=RQ&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.Default)" }{\fldrslt 
{\f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b0 \sa0 \sb0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
Ben A. Fuller
}}}
{\f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b0 \sa0 \sb200 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
, J., denied manufacturer\rquote s motions to dismiss and to compel arbitration. Manufacturer appealed. The Supreme Court, Houston, J., held that: (1) Magnuson-Moss Act did not prohibit enforcement of arbitration clauses in agreements other than warranties; (2) purchasers failed to establish financial hardship; and (3) trial court was to determine validity of arbitration clause; and, on return to remand, held that (4) provision stating that \u8220\'3farbitrator shall have no power to award punitive damages\u8221\'3f was unenforceable and would be severed from rest of agreement; but (5) arbitration clause was valid and enforceable.
\par 
