{\li0 \f2 \qj \b0 \ri0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
{\li0 \f2 \qj \b0 \ri0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
{\f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b0 \sa0 \sb0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
I would like to focus on one portion of the arbitration clause that is the subject of this case and point out a concern that should trouble this Court. The clause, among other things, states:
\par 
}
}
{\li200 \f2 \qj \b0 \ri0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
{\li200 \f2 \qj \b0 \ri0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
{\li1000 \f2 \qj \b0 \ri800 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
{\li1000 \f2 \qj \b0 \ri800 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
{\f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b0 \sa50 \sb250 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
\u8220\'3f[T]he arbitrator shall have no power to award punitive damages or other damages not measured by the prevailing party\rquote s actual damage.\u8221\'3f
\par 
}
}
}
}
}
{\li0 \f2 \qj \b0 \ri0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
{\f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b0 \sa0 \sb200 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
I recognize that in Alabama there is no right to punitive damages; that may explain why this Court found no fault with this portion of the clause. However, this portion troubles me, because I have difficulty seeing a logical end to such waivers.
\par 
}
}
}
{\f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b0 \sa0 \sb0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\li0 \f2 \qj \b0 \ri0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
{\li0 \f2 \qj \b0 \ri0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
{\f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b0 \sa0 \sb0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
If, as in this case, the parties can waive a right to seek punitive damages, then what will prevent a party from drafting an arbitration agreement containing waivers of other kinds of damages? What about damages for emotional distress? What about future damages? What about compensatory damages? What about any damages whatsoever? I understand that I have taken this argument to an extreme, but it is a question that needs to be asked, and the extreme is not an illogical one. If, before a dispute arises, parties to a contract can agree to waive the right to trial by jury, a right guaranteed by both the Alabama Constitution and the United States Constitution, then what possible 
}
{\f2 \b1 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_735_1244_13}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_735_1244_13}
{\f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b1 \sa0 \sb0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
*1244
}
}
{\f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b0 \sa0 \sb0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
 principle of law or contract would prevent them from waiving every single political right that this republic says that the individual is entitled to? Civil rights, rights to property, even the right to liberty, might be subject to contract.
\par 
}
}
}
{\f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b0 \sa0 \sb0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\li0 \f2 \qj \b0 \ri0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
{\li0 \f2 \qj \b0 \ri0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
{\f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b0 \sa0 \sb0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
For example, could an employee waive the right to any damages for a discharge made in retaliation for filing a workers\rquote  compensation claim? The employer makes no demand upon an employee if it demands the agreement prior to employment. If the employee signs such an agreement, why should a court not enforce it? I think the employer could claim an interest in protecting his business\rquote s financial position by preventing lawsuits alleging retaliatory discharge. Could the employee give up rights against racial or sexual discrimination, the duty to report the employer to the police for criminal activity such as an assault upon the employee, the right to a day\rquote s pay for a day\rquote s work, the right to ever leave the job,
}
{\f2 \b0 \fs16 \cf1 \i0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_footnoteReference_B00332001307341_ID0}{\*\bkmkend co_footnoteReference_B00332001307341_ID0}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_B00332001307341_13" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b0 \sa0 \sb0 \fs16 \cf1 \i0 
3
}}}
}
{\f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b0 \sa0 \sb0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
 the right not to have his or her personal effects or home searched?
}
{\f2 \b0 \fs16 \cf1 \i0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_footnoteReference_B00442001307341_ID0}{\*\bkmkend co_footnoteReference_B00442001307341_ID0}
